3	//! `SYS_EXIT` — terminate a target process (slice 4.5, "exit-lite").
4	//!
5	//! PM's kill path ends here: once PM decides a signal's disposition is
6	//! terminate (the no-handler default), it issues `SYS_EXIT` on the target —
7	//! exactly MINIX 3's `pm_exit → sys_exit → clear_proc` shape
8	//! (kernel/system/do_exit.c). The 4.5 subset stops the process permanently
9	//! and detaches it from the IPC machinery it can still be entangled in:
10	//!
11	//! - cancel its `SYS_SETALARM` timer (a stale `EARLIEST_ALARM` cached minimum
12	//!   is harmless — the next gated scan finds no due alarm and recomputes);
13	//! - set `RTS_PROC_STOP` (dequeues via `rts_set` if the target was runnable);
14	//! - if it was blocked `SENDING`, unlink it from the destination's `caller_q`
15	//!   so a terminated proc's queued message is never delivered.
16	//!
17	//! Deferred to 4.6 (alongside `SYS_FORK`'s slot reuse): unblocking receivers
18	//! blocked RECEIVE-from-target with `EDEADSRCDST`, address-space teardown via
19	//! `AddrSpace::destroy`, freeing the slot (`RTS_SLOT_FREE`), and the endpoint
20	//! generation bump. In 4.5 a terminated slot simply stays allocated and
21	//! permanently blocked.
22	//!
23	//! Target-taking (routed beside `SYS_VMCTL` in `kernel_call_dispatch`); trust
24	//! model identical to `do_vmctl` — the `k_call_mask` gate is the only check,
25	//! and PM is the intended sole holder.
26	//!
27	//! ## Message payload layout (offsets within `Message::payload`)
28	//!
29	//! | offset | field                 | direction |
30	//! |--------|-----------------------|-----------|
31	//! |  0..4  | target endpoint (i32) | in        |
